/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `choosing_an_apprenticeships` DISABLE KEYS */;
INSERT INTO `choosing_an_apprenticeships` VALUES (1,'Taking an Apprenticeship doesn’t restrict you to one\r\nspecific job role. During your training you’ll pick up a number of skills\r\nthat’ll make you more attractive to other employers, from basic skills like\r\n<b>teamwork</b> and <b>health and safety awareness</b>, to more specialised capabilities that\r\nwill help you progress through your industry<br><br>All Apprenticeships include:<br><br>A <b>competencies qualification</b>\r\n – to show that you can perform the skill, trade or occupation your \r\nApprenticeship requires. You’ll need to achieve this to qualify for your\r\n Apprenticeship certificate.<br><br>A <b>technical knowledge qualification</b>\r\n – to show you have the necessary technical skills, knowledge and \r\nunderstanding of theoretical concepts as well as knowledge and \r\nunderstanding of the relevant industry and its market.<br><br><b>Key Skills</b> (e.g. team-working, problem solving, communication and using new technology) or <b>Functional Skills</b> to help you achieve a good standard of literacy and numeracy.\r\n<br>\r\n','Except for obvious exceptions like seafishing, most\r\nApprenticeships are offered all over the country. You should be able to find something that suits you in your local area – but\r\nif you want to move somewhere new, an Apprenticeship could be the\r\nideal springboard.','Search for employers that offer Apprenticeship schemes by industry sector or use the regional map to find employers in your area.<br>\r\n','<p>There are three levels of Apprenticeship:</p><p><b>Intermediate Level</b> – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 2 NVQ (equivalent to five GCSEs at grades A–C).</p><p><b>Advanced Level</b> – gain a work-based qualification such as a Level 3 NVQ (equivalent to two A-levels).</p><p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b>\r\n – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 4 NVQ and, in\r\n some cases, a knowledge-based qualification such as a Foundation \r\nDegree.<br></p>','All Apprenticeships deliver <b>high-quality, nationally\r\nrecognised qualifications</b> relevant to the skill, trade or occupation of the learner\r\nand employer.<br><br>As an apprentice you will receive <b>at least 280 hours of\r\nguided learning every year</b>.<br><br>Apprenticeships offer appropriate training to achieve a good\r\nstandard of <b>literacy</b> and <b>numeracy</b> (and <b>ICT</b> where relevant to the skill, trade\r\nor occupation).<br><br><b>Keeping up standards</b><br>The Specification of Apprenticeship Standards for England (SASE)\r\nsets out the minimum requirements to be included in a recognised\r\nApprenticeship, ensuring that every Apprenticeship delivers <b>training that\r\ndirectly meets the needs of employers and learners</b>.\r\n','<b>Salary</b><br>The National Minimum Wage is £2.65 per\r\nhour for apprentices under 19, or those who are aged 19 or over but are in the\r\nfirst year of their Apprenticeship. Many employers will pay you more as you\r\ndevelop your skills and the average apprentice takes home around £170 per week. Research shows that apprentices earn, on average, around\r\n£73,000 more over their lifetime than other employees, and this figure rises to\r\n£100,000 for those who have completed an Advanced Level Apprenticeship.<br><br><b>Funding</b><br>Your employer will pay your salary and support you in your training. Most of your learning will happen at\r\nwork, but some might take place with a training provider. You won’t have to pay any fees: if you are aged between 16 and 18, the\r\nGovernment will pay the full cost of your training (if you’re over 19, your\r\nemployer may be expected to contribute to your training costs). Your employer will work\r\nwith you to try and support your individual requirements.<br>','2012-09-28 16:08:24','2012-11-12 12:01:24');
/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `choosing_an_apprenticeships` ENABLE KEYS */;
UNLOCK TABLES;

