INSERT INTO `what_is_an_apprenticeships` VALUES (1,'<p>Apprenticeships offer a mixture of on and off the job training that will give you the skills you need in your chosen career. There are over 250 Apprenticeship frameworks available, suitable for hundreds of different job roles in over 80 different sectors. From social media to seafishing, or from horticulture to hairdressing, find one that suits you.\r\n</p>','<p>An Apprenticeship is just like  a real job. You’ll work with experienced members of staff to learn the exact skills needed for your chosen career, whether that’s hairdressing, cooking or engineering. As well as learning on the job, you’ll go to a college or training provider, usually on a day-release basis, to study towards a nationally recognised qualification, such as an NVQ. It\'s a perfect mix of theory and practical learning.<br></p>\r\n','There are lots of great reasons to do an Apprenticeship, but here are the big ones:<br><b>Money</b> – You’ll be working for an employer and earning a salary while you learn. Salaries vary, but apprentices earn £170 per week on average.<br><b>Qualifications</b> – You’ll gain nationally recognised \r\nqualifications that will be valid for any employer. You can change jobs \r\nand take your skills and qualifications with you.<br><b>Training</b>\r\n – With an Apprenticeship under your belt, employers will know that \r\nyou’ve got the skills and training needed to do the job and they’ll be \r\nmore likely to hire you.\r\n<br><b>Other perks</b> – You’ll get paid holidays plus pension contributions, subsidised canteen and leisure facilities, etc. – the same benefits as other employees.<br>','<p>There are three levels of Apprenticeship:</p><p><b>Intermediate Level</b> – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 2 NVQ (equivalent to five GCSEs at grades A–C).</p><p><b>Advanced Level</b> – gain a work-based qualification such as a Level 3 NVQ (equivalent to two A-levels).<b><br></b></p><p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b>\r\n – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 4 NVQ and, in\r\n some cases, a knowledge-based qualification such as a Foundation \r\nDegree.</p>\r\n','<b>1. Something for everyone</b> – Worried you won’t find something that interests you? That\r\nshouldn’t be a problem: there are over 250 Apprenticeship schemes available,\r\ncovering pretty much every sort of career.<br><br><b>2. The real world</b> – Lots of people can’t wait to get out of full-time education\r\n– not because they don’t like learning, but because they want to be\r\nout in the world, doing a proper job and earning proper money. An\r\nApprenticeship allows you to do this while still building up skills for the\r\nfuture.<br><b><br>3. Earn while you learn</b> – You’re paid a wage when you do an Apprenticeship, and having\r\nan income will make a major difference to your life.\r\nIt’s money you deserve: you may still be learning, but you’re doing a proper\r\njob and making a real contribution to your employer’s business.<br><b><br>4. Location, location, location</b> – Except for obvious exceptions like seafishing, most\r\nApprenticeships are offered all over the country. You should be able to find something that suits you in your local area – but\r\nif you want to move somewhere new, an Apprenticeship could be the\r\nideal springboard.<br><b><br>5. Building up Britain</b> – Apprenticeships and other forms of vocational training are vital to the British economy: they build up the skills of our\r\nworkforce and keep us competitive at an international level. New standards\r\nquarantee the quality of Apprenticeships and they are\r\nreceiving lots of support from the Government – there’s never been a better\r\ntime to do one.<br><b><br>6. Meet new friends</b> – You’ll mix with a whole new group of people when you take an\r\nApprenticeship. Many companies are very sociable places, and you’ll probably\r\nfind you spend quite a bit of time with your new colleagues outside work. That\r\ndoesn’t mean you’ll lose your old friends, of course, but having new friends\r\ncan only be a bonus.<br><b><br>7. Practical lessons</b> – Taking an Apprenticeship means spending some time in the\r\nclassroom, but the lessons you learn will be directly related to the job you’re\r\ndoing and they’ll help you in your working life. It’s nothing like school:\r\nthese are lessons for professional adults, which is exactly what you’ll be.\r\nYou’ll receive at least 280 hours of guided learning per year.<br><b><br>8. A flying start</b> – You’ll progress much more quickly in your career\r\nif you pick up some formal skills and qualifications along the way. You’ll work\r\nalongside experienced staff to gain job-specific skills. Taking an\r\nApprenticeship means you’ll receive a high-quality, nationally recognised\r\nqualification – such as an NVQ. Getting paid to give yourself a headstart in\r\nthe job market sounds like a pretty good idea.<br><b><br>9. Growing up fast</b> – Many people find that the experience of getting a job\r\nquickly makes them more capable and confident. Having professional\r\nresponsibilities can be challenging, but it’s a positive kind of challenge that\r\nshould make a great difference to your life.<br><b><br>10. Transferable skills</b> – Taking an Apprenticeship doesn’t restrict you to one\r\nspecific job role. During your training you’ll pick up a number of skills\r\nthat’ll make you more attractive to other employers, from basic skills like\r\nteamwork and health and safety awareness, to more specialised capabilities that\r\nwill help you progress through your industry.\r\n','2012-09-27 19:48:16','2012-11-12 11:12:20');
